<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920108-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>920108-0037.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- British Aerospace PLC:   Firm to Sell DAF Stake,   But Not in the Near Future</HL><DATE>01/08/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   B.DAF E.CSA F.ABI F.ASP G.DAI G.MES U.BA U.RVR</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)AUTOMOBILES (AUT)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>BELGIUM (BEL)EUROPE (EU)FRANCE (FR)GERMANY (GE)SPAIN (SP)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   British Aerospace PLC said it would sell its 16% stake inDAF N.V. when &quot;the moment was right.&quot;   The minority stake in the Dutch truck maker doesn't fitstrategically into the British concern's core aerospace,defense, construction and car activities, a company directorsaid. &quot;As a friendly shareholder, we will consult with DAFbefore any sale,&quot; he said. &quot;That is not likely to be in thenear future,&quot; he added.</LP><TEXT>   DAF has suffered from the overall slump in European trucksales, which has hit the U.K. market particularly hard. DAFwas recently reported to have had a considerable loss for1991 after posting a net loss of $102.9 million for the firstsix months.   Meanwhile, British Aerospace officials denied that a saleof U.K. car manufacturer Rover was being considered.   British Aerospace will shake up its commercial aircraftbusiness by splitting manufacturing linked to AirbusIndustrie, the European plane-making consortium, from allother plane-manufacturing activities. This move is scheduledto take place Feb. 1, according to a company official.</TEXT></DOC>